My Math Teacher and the AI App

One day, my math teacher had an interesting idea. He wanted to make math easier and more fun for students, especially when we were learning about linear equations and finding the line of fit. Instead of only using the whiteboard and textbook, he decided to try something new. He used Gemini to help him code an app.

At first, he was not a professional programmer, but he was curious and willing to learn. He typed his ideas into Gemini and explained what kind of app he wanted. He said he needed an app that could let students enter points on a graph, draw a scatter plot, and then find the line of fit. Gemini helped him write the code step by step.

My teacher tested the app many times. Sometimes the graph did not appear correctly, and sometimes the line of fit was in the wrong place. When that happened, he went back to Gemini, asked questions, and fixed the problems. Little by little, the app became better.

Finally, the app was ready for class. We entered different data points, and the app showed us how the points were related. Then it drew a line of fit across the graph. My teacher explained that the line of fit helps us see the general pattern in the data, even if not every point is exactly on the line.

Using the app made the lesson much clearer. We could change the numbers and instantly see how the graph and the line changed. It felt more interactive than just copying notes. My teacher smiled and said that technology can be a powerful learning tool when used in the right way.

That day, I learned not only about linear equations and lines of fit, but also that teachers can keep learning too. My math teacher used Gemini to build something useful, and it made math feel more alive.
